text: We were the last family that came from Germany in 1952. We were the last family that they took to America. I remember it because we have pictures and articles about how my grandparents were so lucky that they were able to go to America. I think we were the last family. That's why. We were the last family that came to America. My grandmother came a year earlier. But my mother took the child and my brother was born in November before that. I think the truth is that it was because of that. Since we were the last family, when the Hungarian revolution came and Hungary began to bring the refugees, we were invited to New York. I remember it so well. I was 7 or 8 years old. We were in the US. We wore American flags and we greeted them. It was especially exciting for me because I was so young. For the first time I was in a hotel somewhere. We received a very nice response. We did interviews and so on. I think since we were the last family, we became Flying Tiger Airlines. I know that we flew over Irimaa. We had to fly over Irimaa because there was something wrong with the propeller. Or something was a problem. But then we got better again. I don't think we were there for very long. Maybe more than a night or something. And then we flew back to New York. So we don't have that ship story either. Then we were immediately taken by buses to Seabrook. Seabrook is a small village in Lona, New Jersey. It's about 3-4 hours by bus. We took a bus from New York. We went to Seabrook because there was a company called Seabrook Farms. Charles F. Seabrook had been building a large farm for over 30-40 years. He had a cold factory there. It was the first cold factory in the US. It was built with a cold plant and a cold plant. And he needed a job. And he needed a job especially in the summer months when it was winter. When everything was growing. Before the Estonians appeared there. The Japanese had come there. And the Japanese, because when America was at war with Japan. Then the Japanese also put them in the slaughterhouses. Because the Japanese who lived in America. Because America was at war with Japan. They started to slaughter here. Or they started to slaughter more. Maybe, you know, to connect with Japan. To do some kind of big jobs. Or I don't know what they did. They were Japanese who had lived for years. They had their own homes, their own houses. And it had to be like moving too. Not only, you know, like moving to Russia. Anyway, they put them in warehouses. They were told to take what you can carry with you. And they were in warehouses for a few years. And then when the war ended. Then they were given, you know, go now. Live. Search. Of course, their homes and places where they had already been. They couldn't go back there anymore. Whether they had been liquidated or sold. Maybe some of them got alone. But basically they had to start a new life. So they came to Seabrook. Because Seabrook offered them jobs. And living. In the middle of the 1950s. There were about 600 people there. 600 Estonians. In my opinion. I have read somewhere. That at least 1000 Estonians ever moved through there. Some people came there only for a couple of months. And moved on. Maybe they got contact with other people. Or some better job. But we lived there. I lived there for 12 years. I think that's why my father had a good place to live. When people came there. They were given a place to live. There were furniture inside. There was a toilet. There was a toilet. All sorts of things. They were given. There was a well. Where they could buy food. What they needed. Welfare was there. And my friends were there when I was growing up. Estonians. And Estonians. And we were there in school. Like beggars. We were always in the first class. In the first classes. We had a very strong Estonian life there. You were in the Estonian Sunday school. That worked on Saturdays. But there was a church component. But also in Estonian. A little bit of practice. Singing in Estonian. National dance. All sorts of things. Estonian culture. And Estonian books. Packages in Estonia. It was a big part of my life. To get a package in Estonia. I remember how we gathered for several months. What to get. What was needed in Estonia. Is it possible to get some extra money. Then of course the money from which we had grown up. Which was still in such a good condition. Especially since it was me. And finally I had three brothers. Two brothers were born in Sibruk. Always a coffee bag. Definitely. I don't know where they went. It took a long time to plan. How to put it in there. And then finally making the package. And then some kind of line around it. So that it would be solid. And then the address. And then maybe one. I don't know if I had to go to Philadelphia. I think I had to go somewhere far away to get it. Where I could get it in Europe or in Estonia. When I was six years old. I think my first books started to go back and forth. I remember that my grandfather Herman Merikani Öde who still lived in Tartu had changed his name a bit. He was called Merikandi. Because he was not related to the fact that he was my grandfather's relative. The grandfather who was a police officer. And the books always went so that in the beginning the book wasn't for my grandfather. You know, at some point I was able to name who I was supposed to write to. Because there was always this feeling that I didn't want to do bad in Estonia. That someone who was a soldier in the German army or in the police or whatever was in contact with them. The books were read and understood by my mother and grandmother. What was going on there and what was going on here. And they reminded me of Estonian times. And what I always remembered was that my mother always had different memories of things. It was like this today. No, it wasn't like this today. It was like this today. What do you know? You were so young, you couldn't remember anything. No, I know very well. You know, those things. The thing I grew up with and my mother was, oh, she was such a big fan of communists, Russians, red things. And I didn't want to wear red. That was for sure. But my mother was, oh, she was 16 when she left. And plus, she has this thing, I've heard so much about it, that she had been deported. She was probably killed right away, very quickly. One father died, and the tree, where she was buried, the other, those who were deported from the village, she had three children. And the mother died on the tree. At least, my mother's story was always that she was thrown out of the tree as a dead child. When you grow up as a refugee, I remember that, yes, friends with whom you grow up, who are not Estonians, for example, Americans, they have grandparents, they have grandparents, they have fathers, you read children's stories, oh, let's go up to Pöning, let's see what old things are there. I didn't have any of these things. We didn't have any old things anywhere. We only had the things we had when we came. We didn't have any old memories of this country. All our things were in Estonia, our memories, our Pöning, our old things, our relatives. So, this coming to Estonia was a homecoming to a person who had never been there, but it was a homecoming. You finally come down from the ship and then you see that there is this, I don't know if it was a wheel, but wheels, and you are on this side and you see through it, it was a wheelbarrow. And I immediately stepped in and everyone was standing in line. And I felt them all. I hadn't seen them in my life, but I had grown up with books, like my grandparents, my grandmother, my mother, we were talking about them all the time. I stood there and said, listen, Livi, Elmo, Kai, Matti, and there were a lot of people who, even if you have grown up a little, but haven't seen them in your life, but they are your own right now. And I was very surprised because I looked at them and I saw them all. And I thought, well, I'm not going to be a hero. And I said to myself, I don't want to be a hero. I want to be a hero. And I said, yes, I'm a hero, but I don't want to be a hero. And I said,
